{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538168"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16154"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16154"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.08,0.14,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101472"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8845"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4699"},{"type":"tags","id":"4701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101472"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to a sexual health clinic requesting HIV post-exposure prophylaxis. He reports unprotected sexual intercourse 24 hours ago with a casual partner whom he knows to be HIV positive and not on treatment. The patient is prescribed daily pre-exposure prophylaxis but admits to missing tablets. He states that his last tablet was 72 hours ago and that he has had three doses in the last seven days. He has no significant medical history and takes no other regular medications. He has no known drug allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence post-exposure prophylaxis","Re-check kidney function before commencing post-exposure prophylaxis","Advise to restart daily PrEP immediately","Take the one missed dose of PrEP as well as today\u0027s dose","Defer treatment until HIV testing is completed"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a clear indication for post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) despite the patient being prescribed pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP). The key risk factors include unprotected sexual intercourse with a known HIV-positive partner with a detectable viral load, and poor adherence to PrEP. In patients having anal intercourse, four doses of PrEP must be taken per week to be effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence post-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. PEP should be initiated as soon as possible within 72 hours of exposure. Even though the patient is prescribed PrEP, his poor adherence means he cannot rely on its protective effects. PEP typically consists of a three-drug antiretroviral regimen taken for 28 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERe-check kidney function before commencing post-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E would cause unnecessary delay in initiating PEP. Since the patient is already prescribed PrEP, he would be undergoing regular kidney function monitoring as part of standard PrEP care. Delaying PEP to check kidney function is not appropriate given the time-sensitive nature of PEP effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvise to restart daily PrEP\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient as PrEP is most effective when taken consistently and may not provide adequate protection after a high-risk exposure when adherence has been poor. Simply restarting PrEP would not address the immediate risk from this exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETake the one missed dose of PrEP as well as today\u0027s dose\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate protection. Taking catch-up doses of PrEP after a high-risk exposure is not an evidence-based strategy for preventing HIV transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefer treatment until HIV testing is completed\u003C/strong\u003E would delay the initiation of PEP beyond the optimal window for effectiveness. PEP is most effective in the first 24 hours following HIV exposure but is still effective if initiated up to 72 hours. While baseline HIV testing should be performed, it should not delay the commencement of PEP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating PEP, the patient should be counselled about the importance of medication adherence, both for the PEP course and future PrEP use. Follow-up HIV testing should be arranged, and consideration given to sexually transmitted infection screening.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) should be initiated within 72 hours of HIV exposure, even in patients who are prescribed pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP).","Poor adherence to PrEP (missing multiple doses) reduces its effectiveness in preventing HIV transmission.","A detectable viral load in the source partner increases HIV transmission risk significantly."],"references":["Molina JM, Capitant C, Spire B, Pialoux G, Cotte L, Charreau I, et al. On-Demand Preexposure Prophylaxis in Men at High Risk for HIV-1 Infection. New England Journal of Medicine [Internet]. 2015 Dec 3;373(23):2237\u201346. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26624850/","Moore M, Stansfield S, Donnell DJ, Boily MC, Mitchell KM, Anderson PL, Delany-Moretlwe S, Bekker LG, Mgodi NM, Celum CL, Dimitrov D. Efficacy estimates of oral pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV prevention in cisgender women with partial adherence. Nat Med. 2023 Nov;29(11):2748-2752. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37798438/","Sultan B, Benn P, Waters L. Current perspectives in HIV post-exposure prophylaxis. HIV AIDS (Auckl). 2014 Oct 24;6:147-58. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4216036/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16154"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T01:58:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T01:58:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8845"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101472"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type